I regret to inform everyone but support for the FCC Twitch channel will diminish significantly. I know longer will be working to get more content and campers onto the Twitch channel. Nah I think we need to diferenciate between the official content and the misc streams. These misc streams should be let do music and not exporting the videos to you tube. My reasoning for this is that someone on there own is going to have a lot of dead air or just end up distracted/waffling. It's gonna be a much smaller number of people lost to poor music choice than to silence. I do think we should limit the types of music. I.e. No death metal/really heavy rap

Additionally, just like some people change the radio channel if they don't like the music, some may change the stream for the same reason. (I frequently do). We want a diverse audience in as many ways as possible, including musical taste, and we could be losing viewers without realizing because they don't like the music.If they really want to listen to music, they can do that from their own computer.

A4: I would love for us to do more of these streams, but I think instead of marathons, we should plan consistent blocks of time - a minimum of 3 hours and we just keep going if we feel like it. These should be on Friday, Saturday and Sunday (peak time) - especially Sunday afternoon and evening I think. The marathon was fun and memorable, but I think we can break it up and make it a bit easier on ourselves so we can reliably stream over week after week.

A3: I was surprised at how much progress you all made on the game. It was actually pretty fun to play! I was also surprised by the fact that we didn’t ever really spike, we mostly hovered around 40 viewers for the entire weekend.

A1: c9.io was an awesome choice and the ability to collaborate AND play the game as it was developed was magical
A2: Planning. We were short on time, yes, but in retrospect actually trying to cover the midnight hours was probably a mistake. I had fun playing coding games (codingame.com) during the 4 hours or so I could stay up, but solving coding puzzles and sleep deprivation make for bad viewing. I had like 45 viewers at 6 a.m. EST when I shut down the stream, and I felt really guilty about it, but I could barely keep my eyes open :worried:

As for the questions now that my ramble is over :P

I think that the results from the weekend can be divided and evaluated from two points of view. FCC the twitch channel and FCC the business. For FCC the twitch channel a lot of good content went out to reach a lot of new people and grew the channel more than anything else in the past not including the saturday summit. The other side to this is that on reflection 80 hours spread over something like a 2-5 hour stream each day time so that it's on around when the US is home from work would yield a better result. This kinda leads into FCC the business. From an organizational and human stand point it took a lot out of all involved but this is most likely a result of a small group of people stretching to fit a large window of time which was pure circumstance. As for the actual conversions into meaningful site visits(arguable the most important metric) the result was good but underwhelming when compared with the amount of work/time involved but again i think by spreading out the content and streaming at more lucrative times we could get more out of less work.

A1: I think we did a great job of planning the stream in such a short time period. All of us did a great job keeping the viewers engaged and constantly providing content and material to the stream.

A2:  I think we could plan better, but considering the short period I would not consider this as a fault, just a time issue. We could do a better job of uptime (I think mainly me :( ) but along side this I believe we need to find a better way to transition the stream.

A3: The amount of collaborators be had on C9 was something I did not anticipate. I was overjoyed by the amount of support we received from all of the campers on and off C9. I also didn't anticipate the near completion of the game (while not complete, I think we are at a alpha finished stage).

A4: Of course! I do not think I would like to do another marathon anytime soon. I am sooooooooo tired. But I would love to stream more on the FCC and collaborate with other streams to come up with great streams and content in the future all around Game Dev, at least for twitch.
A4: Absolutely.
A3: The amount of people who supported us and who helped us (by helping in c9 or just in Twitch chat) was something I didn't expect a lot.
A2: I would say the planning. We didn't have enough streamers to fill up all of the time and it was unclear what others were planning on doing.
A1: I would say the programming itself and the communication with the chat.

We are looking to add a new member to our core team!

#Title: Live Coding Coordinator#
##Type: Volunteer##
##Status: Core Team##

##Responsibilities:##

###Marketing###
- Manage Free Code Camp's branding and content on Twitch.tv and LiveCoding.tv
- Come up with cool ideas for content, marathons, and competitions
- Use access to Free Code Camp's official Twitter account (~15k followers!) and Facebook account for sharing streaming-related announcements and updates.
- Write Field Guide articles that give tips for successful streaming
- Pimp out Moobot and expand playlist and autoresponses. Consider use of Nightbot and other bots.

###Security and moderation###
- Maintain the security of Twitch and LiveCoding and ensure that passwords are changed as streamers come and go
- Appoint mods and exercise final judgement on banning disruptive viewers
- Vet campers who would like to stream with us, and upon your approval, onboard new streamers with OBS and other tools

##Requirements##
- Must be an active Free Code Camp camper who has streamed with us before. 
- Must be a generally chill person who is passionate about coding. 
- Must typically be available to stream or at least by phone in case of emergency on Friday nights and all day Saturday and Sunday (these are prime time)
- Must be willing to commit for at least 3 months.

If you are interested in this position on Free Code Camp's core team, please message @quincylarson in Gitter

Here are some other reasons we should stick with everything we're doing on Twitch, but focus on game development:

1) A secondary chatroom or radio station simply won't work with Twitch's growing mobile base. I suspect an outsized portion of mobile viewers are commuters - that is, busy people. Making twitch inaccessbile to them would be a mistake.

2) We can pair program, keep code JavaScript, keep using a radio station and publicizing our stream everywhere we already are - but these would all be focused toward the goal of building cool games with some of the amazing JavaScript game development libraries out there.

3) Games are a proven gateway into programming. Most coders are or were gamers. Many people got into coding because they wanted to make games.

4) Live coding is a small market compared to Twitch. Even with their acceptance into Ycombinator, and all the press they've gotten, and the network-effects nature of their product, they only have about the same amount of traffic that Free Code Camp does. You could also argue that many of their users are actively looking to learn to code, and are much more likely to discover us through all our other channels.

5) Since games are inherently more exciting and captivating than enterprise web applications, they are better suited for streaming. They are more visual.

Frankly, we'll it will be an uphill battle to an average of ~500 concurrent viewers to regularly get featured on Twitch and become a partner if we stick to non-gaming programming. But I've seen plenty of cases where someone coding games had hundreds of viewers.

##Game development is much more popular on Twitch than non-game development.##

People go to Twitch to watch people play games. The most common interest Twitch users have is gaming. Development is only tangentially related to gaming - but Game Development is much more closely related.

I have some input on all of this but it's 3:41am and I'm about to head to bed. I'll collect my thoughts tomorrow :)

So to summarize this long stream of conscious:
1) Maybe we should do multi-platform streaming (perhaps we could have a cloud computer that we stream from that has OBS and everything - then everyone could drop into the same environment?)
2) If we do, we should pool all viewers into a Gitter room (creating a GitHub account and authenticating takes only a few seconds, and that quickly draws them into our greater Free Code Camp ecosystem)
3) Instead of streaming audio through Twitch/LiveCoding/Youtube, we should have a global request-driven radio station.
4) We should aim for 24/7 coverge - all in English, all focused on JavaScript development. No need for a schedule, it would be spontaneous and fun. Campers could essentially tag in and out.
Another cool aspect of the stream is our ability to pull our viewers onto the stream with Screen Hero. We could coordinate this in real time with the chat room.
All of this could be plugged into an /FreeCodeCampLive and it would be where we manipulate the radio station and discuss the stream.

Regarding the radio station, I would like to create an FCC radio station that is request driven, where all the songs are requested by campers. Something like how Moobot accepts youtube video requests, queues them up, then plays them. Something that shows who requested the song, and gives people the ability to thank them.
This is one situation where it could actually be advantageous to stream on multiple platforms (twitch, youtube, livecoding) and pool everyone into one big chat room.

Also, Twitch chat sucks, and I think we should create a Gitter channel for this, plus a way to fast-track people into that room. That way as people arrive, we can tell them to hop into the Gitter Chat, where everything will be persisted and indexed by google, and where they’ll have better tools for expressing themselves (markdown, images, etc.)

Another thing I’d like to point out is that Youtube is a massive site with tons of traffic. We could essentially stitch together “highlight videos” of streaming sessions and put them on Youtube. The main challenge is copyrighted music and the audio issue. I am interested in hearing what you all have to say about this.

There are technical solutions to trying to stream on both channels at once, and I have no doubt we could engineer such a solution. My concern is livecoding.tv may attract a more technical audience, where Twitch is probably attracting a more casual audience (those people we steer there through Twitter and watchpeoplecode.com). 

It’s no secret at this point that our goal is to have 24/7 coding on Twitch, and I think we could achieve that as our community grows (currently about 10% week-on-week). Once we’re able to achieve 24/7 coverage, it would only be a few more weeks before we could have 24/7 coverage both on Twitch and on Livecoding.tv. So my question is - instead of trying to find a technical solution, perhaps we should be finding more campers who are interested in streaming and helping them get set up. For example, @Azimoto9 streamed for a few hours earlier and it was really good stuff!

\#sorryAboutTheLongWindedDebateWithMyself

So I thought long and hard before throwing my two cents into the ring with much banging of heads on desks but here it is. I feel personally as someone who found FCC through twitch that leaving the service is not a good idea. We just recently got the ability to offer quality options to the end users so there has been enough channel growth to warrant twitch giving this to us. On the other hand the obvious benefits of jumping to a more programming-focused service with a lot more fresh new faces would inevitably drive a fairly large amount of new users and new interest in FCC in the short term with the potential for a long term steady but higher flow but that will depend on the success on the service that is chosen as a replacement. We also must keep in mind at this point that FCC has now killed one chat client and almost a second one so a small streaming service suddenly facing the might of the Saturday summit may buckle under the strain whereas we know that twitch doesn't even bat an eyelid at that sort of stuff. The fact that there is no one really clear benefit of one over the other leaves the only, and my opinion the best option of streaming to two services at once. I'm no legal expert so take what i say with a grain of salt but there is nothing in the twitch terms of service that says that you cannot broadcast elsewhere. So the real challenge is how can the multi pal broadcast system work for everyone. Taking the average computer of everyone in this room/has ever streamed I'm going to work off the assumption that we all have laptops with the low end i5s and 8GB of RAM. Now when it comes to how can the dual/triple broadcast be achieved the obvious option is to multi-instance OBS. The equally obvious issue with this is that even with the recent performance optimizations that have been made people have been finding their computer struggling with running OBS and working at the same time which is understandable as OBS is a resource hog. What then came to me is the idea of everyone streaming to a man in the middle ( https://obsproject.com/forum/resources/how-to-easily-stream-to-two-or-more-locations-using-nginx.11/ ) and it then servers out the singular broadcast to twitch + whoever. The only issue with this is that to build such a system is going to cost FCC some amount of money. The only way it could be free/cheap is to piggy back off FCC's server to run this set up. I do think this is a possibility and i deserves some further investigation and I'm fully willing to work on a prototype once the launch of the new course ware stuff is complete. Feel free to tell me I'm an idiot / add or detract from this! I think though  it will allow the best of both worlds
